Title = {Structuring Smart Cities From an Electrical Perspective: An Integrative
   Framework},
Journal = {IEEE ACCESS},
Year = {2025},
Volume = {13},
Pages = {183184-183199},
Abstract = {The concept of smart cities has evolved as a response to complex urban
   challenges, incorporating technological, environmental, economic, and
   institutional dimensions to improve urban quality of life and
   resilience. In parallel, the energy sector has undergone significant
   transformations driven by decarbonization, decentralization, and
   digitalization. Despite these advances, urban systems and energy
   infrastructure are still addressed as separate domains, limiting the
   understanding of how electricity systems support digital urban services
   in practice. This paper aims to provide an integrative overview of the
   relationship between smart cities and modern electrical systems. The
   contribution lies in articulating how key components such as smart
   grids, distributed energy resources, electric mobility, and digital
   technologies relate to urban governance, mobility, and service delivery.
   The analysis is based on a conceptual survey, exploring intersections,
   complementarities, and emerging patterns across both domains. The
   results underscore the mutual interdependence between energy and urban
   systems, emphasizing the importance of interoperability, coordinated
   planning, and infrastructure integration. By organizing these elements
   within a unified perspective, the paper reinforces the role of
   electricity as a structural pillar in the smart city context and
   supports the development of future interdisciplinary research,
   monitoring approaches, and policy design.},
